div.p:
I spare to speake what further right you haue in mee, and how much I am beholding (in my particular) to the example of your integrity and conscionable course of life, of your great and continuall paines, humility, and modesty euery way, you being as eminent in and for humilitie, as humble in eminency of gifts. But I dare not presume to presse these while I praise them: I know you had rather so bee, then be knowne to bee, further then Gods glory and the necessity of the Church requires; and so you neither are nor can be vnknowne. I will conclude, propounding the example of your wonderfull diligence and constant paines, as also modesty, to such as in the Ministery seeke their owne ease, and follow their pleasures, and by the Ministery seeke dignities and preferments to themselues. Doubtlesse labouring with like singlenesse of heart and modesty of minde, they should finde little cause to doubt so much of Gods Prouidence, as to despaire of Prouision proportionable to their gifts. You haue found it vnsought
for, but shall finde the fruit and reward much more hereafter. 〈 in non-Latin alphabet 〉 . I will not presume to stirre vp you, but my selfe, and other sluggards, in and with the words of Ignatius, Ignat. epist. 1. to one Mary,
〈 in non-Latin alphabet 〉 . And thus I end.
